when you earn money at work, some money is taken out of your original pay. these are called deductions. they are legal and required. deductions earning for some jobs (usually full-time), you can choose to have money taken out of your paycheck for benefits such as health care, dental care, or help with transportation. you and your employer share the cost. benefits the government takes money out of your paycheck to pay for services that benefit everyone, like roads, buses, schools, and the refugee resettlement program. taxes

earning how much will she earn? fatima earns $720.00 every two weeks, but the hotel takes $163.00 out of her check to pay taxes to the government. $720.00 - $163.00 = $557.00 fatima also gets health insurance from her employer, which is another $45.00 each pay period. $557.00  $45.00 = $512.00 so fatima receives a paycheck of $508.00 after paying taxes and benefits.

something you desire or enjoy, but not something you need to survive. wants something that is required for survival - you cannot live without it. needs knowing the difference between wants and needs will help you spend money wisely.  wants vs. needs you will have to make daily choices about how you spend your money.  needs vs. wants spending need want

what is a budget? spending a budget is a way to track money coming in and out of your household. if your expenses are lower than your income, you can save or spend the extra money!  keep expenses lower than income complete and update your budget once a month to keep track of your spending. budget often always plan to include money in your budget for savings whenever possible. budget to save
february budget spending ernesto and maria made a family budget to track their income and expenses.  whats wrong with their budget?
reduce expenses spending tap each of the pictures to find out what you can do to reduce expenses:

electricity/gas spending ways to reduce household expenses with electricity and gas: turn off the lights before you leavethe house unplug appliances when not in use turn the heat down use a fan in the summer unless it is really hot  then use the ac

transportation spending ways to reduce household expenses with transportation: compare public transportation options  a monthly bus or train pass may be cheaper than day passes walk or bike as much as possible

food spending ways to reduce household expenses with food: compare product prices and find the cheapest grocery store near you buy things that are off-brand or on sale buy items in bulk avoid convenience stores (small stores) which are usually more expensive buy less junk food look for coupons and use a bonus card for discounts
clothing spending ways to reduce household expenses with clothing: look for thrift stores or donationresources ask your caseworker if they have clothing donations
cigarettes spending ways to reduce household expenses with cigarettes: cigarettes are a huge expense and are also very bad for your health

electronics spending ways to reduce household expenses with electronics: wait to buy children phones until they are old enough and will be responsible cut cost for cable and sign up for discounted internet and computer instead reduce time spent using technology
march budget spending ernesto and maria worked hard to reduce their expenses and now their budget is balanced. income = expenses
march budget spending how did ernesto and maria reduce their expenses? cancelled cable tv channels turned the heat down 3 degrees found community resource offering donated items

ways to spend money spending you can use your debit card to withdraw money at the atm or make purchases.  debit card you can write a check - an official note that promises money from one person to another.  checks you can use cash - physical money; dollars and cents, in bills and coins. cash there are 3 ways you can spend your money:

an atm is a computer that lets you withdraw cash from your bank account.  atms have a screen, number pad, a place to insert your debit card, and slots that dispense money and a receipt.  each atm looks a bit different.  to avoid fees, use your banks atms. what is an atm? spending

whenever you withdraw cash from an atm, you should do a few things to keep yourself and your money safe!  staying safe at the atm spending dont carry more than $40.00 in your wallet or pocket, because you cannot replace cash if it is stolen.  dont carry too much cash check to make sure no one is looking over your shoulder. check behind you cover your hand when you type your pin number.  cover your pin

you may find other ways to spend money in your daily lives. some of these services are offered through a phone app, and others are available online or in-person.  tap each image to view more information about each way to spend money. other ways to spend  spending

money orders spending these are similar to checks, but are guaranteed by a bank or post office. you usually pay a fee to purchase a money order. some rental companies require money orders for rent payments. if you lose a money order, its like losing cash.
venmo spending venmo is a phone application that allows friends and family to send and receive money between their bank accounts.

money orders spending a common service to wire (send) money from one person to another. western union has many in-person branch locations. this is common for sending money to people in other countries.
paypal spending this service is available on smartphones or computers. it allows you to make and receive payments through your paypal account, which is connected to your bank account.

terms.title: ATM
terms.Text: A computer that does some of the same functions and tasks as a bank employee. You can access your account from an ATM to withdraw cash, deposit checks, or see your account balance.

terms.title: Bank Account
terms.Text: The place where a financial institution protects and maintains the money of an individual or company.

terms.title: Benefits
terms.Text: Services provided through an employer, such as health insurance or retirement savings. You and the employer share the costs and money is taken out of your paycheck.

terms.title: Budget
terms.Text: A monthly financial plan for your household that specifies income and expenses.

terms.title: Cash
terms.Text: A physical form of money; in the USA, the currency is dollars and cents, in bills and coins.

terms.title: Check
terms.Text: An official paper note that promises money from one person/business to another. Employers give employees checks for work, but checks are also used between individuals. Checks are replaceable and therefore safer than cash.

terms.title: Checking Account
terms.Text: An account in a financial institution that is active  money is deposited and withdrawn regularly. Checks and debit cards are linked to a Checking Account.

terms.title: Debit Card
terms.Text: A card linked to your checking account. You can use your debit card to withdraw money at the ATM or make purchases.

terms.title: Deductions
terms.Text: Money that is legally kept out of a paycheck that goes to taxes or benefits.

terms.title: Deposit
terms.Text: An amount of money placed in a bank account.

terms.title: Income
terms.Text: All money coming into your household, from work earnings, public benefits, or other sources.

terms.title: Paycheck
terms.Text: A method of payment from an employer. Paychecks usually come in set intervals of time, such as every 2 weeks.

terms.title: Paystub
terms.Text: The receipt of the paycheck, with more details about work earnings, taxes, and benefits.

terms.title: PIN Number
terms.Text: A four-digit number that you need in order to use your debit card. This number should be secret.

terms.title: Savings Account
terms.Text: An account in a financial institution that earns interest and is not accessed frequently.

terms.title: Taxes
terms.Text: The part of your income that goes to the government, to provide beneficial services such as roads or schools.

terms.title: Withdraw
terms.Text: Taking cash out of your account, usually at an ATM or a bank.
